{
  "text": "Helicobacter pylori infection was made if Helicobacter pylori bacteria were seen on both histopathological examinations and the rapid urease test was positive. A recent study from India attempted to define the gold standard of diagnostic tests to determine Helicobacter pylori infection status by breaking down the respective sensitivities and specificities. Both sensitivity and specificity of nested PCR have been reported to be 100%. In contrast, the sensitivity and specificity of serological, urea breath, fecal antigen, rapid urease tests, histopathology, PCR, and culture have been found to be 85% and 79%, 75%-100% and 77%-100%, 67%-100% and 61%-100%, 75%-100% and 84%-100%, 66%-100% and 94%-100%, 75%-100% and 84%-100%, and 55%-56% and 100%, respectively [CITATION_1] . PCR does not seem to be feasible in daily clinical practice; thus we chose in our study patients to consider them Helicobacter pylori negative if they had negative results in one or both of the above selected tests.",
